{
  "texts": [
    "In the broader life sciences, fluorescence Microscopy carries the advantage of enabling the capture dynamic processes in live samples, with modern confocal and two-photon imaging systems minimizing sample damage due to photo bleaching and/ or toxicity through precise focusing of excitation light.",
    "In fossils its efficacy is likely to be strongly impacted by the taphonomy (preservation) of the sample, with studies being reliant upon sample autofluorescence rather than preparation with fluorophore doping to obtain contrast.",
    "In DL, the ability to highlight conventionally low contrast features (e.g., anatomical components occluded by matrix, organic residues) presents unique opportunities to enrich the feature sets of input images beyond their visible signatures (Waters 2009), though the reliance upon the intrinsic presence of fluorescent markers within the sample selected for training may severely limit the scope of pertinent studies (Petty 2007).",
    "X-ray computed tomography employs X-rays to generate a series of radiographs (projections) captured through a specimen from multiple angles along a radial scan path.",
    "Projections are then reconstructed into tomographic volumes, typically using either filtered back-projection or iterative reconstruction techniques, providing a three-dimensional representation of fossil structure."
  ]
}